# Order Processing Model

## Overview

Order processing begins once purchase orders pass validation and are entered into internal systems such as ERP platforms.

This stage transforms purchase orders into executable operational records used by fulfillment, logistics, and financial systems.

---

## Core Processing Activities

Order processing typically includes the following steps:

1. ERP order creation  
2. inventory availability confirmation  
3. order allocation  
4. fulfillment release  
5. shipment scheduling  

Each step prepares the order for physical fulfillment and shipment execution.

---

## ERP System Integration

Most wholesale organizations manage order processing through enterprise systems such as:

• NetSuite  
• SAP  
• Sage  
• Microsoft Dynamics  

These systems allow operations teams to track order status, inventory availability, and financial data.

---

## Inventory Allocation

Once an order is entered into the system, inventory must be allocated to fulfill the order.

Allocation processes ensure that:

• available inventory is reserved  
• high-priority customers receive product  
• allocation conflicts are minimized

---

## Fulfillment Release

After allocation, the order is released to warehouse or fulfillment teams.

Fulfillment teams then prepare the order for shipment through picking, packing, labeling, and shipment preparation.

---

## Operational Coordination

Order processing requires coordination across several teams including:

• order operations  
• inventory planning  
• warehouse operations  
• logistics teams  
• finance teams  

Clear communication between these teams ensures orders move through the system efficiently.

---

## Importance of Process Discipline

A well-defined order processing model ensures that:

• orders move consistently through the workflow  
• systems maintain accurate records  
• operational errors are minimized  
• fulfillment teams receive accurate instructions

This stage connects digital order records with physical product movement.
